.TH "ELEMENT.PART" "3JS" "November 25, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Element.part \- Element: part property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The read\-only \f[B]\f[CB]part\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]Element\f[R] interface contains a \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R] object
representing the part identifier(s) of the element.
It reflects the element\(cqs \f[CR]part\f[R] content attribute.
These can be used to style parts of a shadow DOM, via the
\f[CR]::part\f[R] pseudo\-element.
.SH VALUE
A \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R] object.
If the \f[CR]part\f[R] attribute is not set or empty, it returns an
empty \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R], i.e., a \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R] with the
\f[CR]length\f[R] property equal to \f[CR]0\f[R].
.PP
Although the \f[CR]part\f[R] property itself is read\-only in the sense
that you can\(cqt replace the \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R] object, you can
still assign to the \f[CR]part\f[R] property directly, which is
equivalent to assigning to its \f[CR]value\f[R] property.
You can also modify the \f[CR]DOMTokenList\f[R] object using the
\f[CR]add()\f[R], \f[CR]remove()\f[R], \f[CR]replace()\f[R], and
\f[CR]toggle()\f[R] methods.
.SH EXAMPLES
The following excerpt is from our \c
.UR https://mdn.github.io/web-components-examples/shadow-part/
shadow\-part
.UE \c
\ example.
Here the \f[CR]part\f[R] attribute is used to find the shadow parts, and
the \f[CR]part\f[R] property is then used to change the part identifiers
of each tab so the correct styling is applied to the active tab when
tabs are clicked.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] tabs = [];
\f[B]const\f[R] children = \f[B]this\f[R].shadowRoot.children;

\f[B]for\f[R] (\f[B]const\f[R] elem \f[B]of\f[R] children) {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (elem.getAttribute(\(dqpart\(dq)) {
    tabs.push(elem);
  }
}

tabs.forEach((tab) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  tab.addEventListener(\(dqclick\(dq, (e) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    tabs.forEach((tab) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
      tab.part = \(dqtab\(dq;
    });
    e.target.part = \(dqtab active\(dq;
  });

  console.log(tab.part);
});
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
